---
import DeepDiveLayout from '../../../features/engine/deep/DeepDiveLayout.astro';
---

<DeepDiveLayout
  title="Scaling &amp; Retrieval"
  subtitle="Before the pipeline: what scaling laws taught us."
  notebooks="NB-01, NB-02"
  prevSlug="dead-ends"
  prevTitle="What Didn't Work"
>

  <section class="deep-section">
    <h2>Where It Started</h2>
    <p>
      Before SHGAT and GRU, there was a simpler question: can node retrieval
      be solved with embedding similarity alone? NB-01 and NB-02 are the
      origin story — the experiments that showed why a learned approach
      was necessary at all.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="scaling-panels reveal-on-scroll">
    <div class="scaling-panel">
      <div class="scaling-panel-header">
        <span class="scaling-nb">NB-01</span>
        <span class="scaling-topic">Message Passing Toy Problem</span>
      </div>
      <p class="scaling-body">
        The earliest message passing experiment: a synthetic hypergraph with
        controlled structure. Validated that SHGAT-style attention could learn
        to weight neighbors by structural role, not just semantic similarity.
        Five nodes. Three capability levels. Gradient check passed.
      </p>
      <p class="scaling-body">
        The toy problem was intentionally small to verify the mathematics
        before investing in a full training pipeline. It served its purpose:
        message passing works in theory.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scaling-panel">
      <div class="scaling-panel-header">
        <span class="scaling-nb">NB-02</span>
        <span class="scaling-topic">Hierarchical Workflow Retrieval</span>
      </div>
      <p class="scaling-body">
        The retrieval baseline: given a user intent, retrieve the most similar
        workflow using cosine similarity over mean-pooled node embeddings.
        Tested at three scales: 50 workflows, 200 workflows, 1,000 workflows.
      </p>
      <p class="scaling-body">
        Retrieval accuracy degrades sub-linearly with scale — but it degrades.
        At 1,000 workflows, cosine similarity over flat embeddings plateaus.
        The problem is not the retrieval mechanism; it is that flat embeddings
        cannot encode the sequential structure of node co-execution. This is
        the gap SHGAT was designed to fill.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="cinema-grid reveal-on-scroll">
    <figure class="cinema cinema-compact">
      <img src="/images/engine/deep/scaling/mp-toy-results.png"
           alt="Message passing toy problem results: 5-node synthetic graph gradient check" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption><strong>NB-01 · Toy results.</strong> SHGAT attention learns to weight by structural role. Gradient check passed on a 5-node synthetic hypergraph.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure class="cinema cinema-compact">
      <img src="/images/engine/deep/scaling/workflow-retrieval-results.png"
           alt="Hierarchical workflow retrieval accuracy at 50, 200, 1000 workflows" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption><strong>NB-02 · Retrieval scaling.</strong> Cosine similarity over flat embeddings plateaus at 1,000 workflows. The gap that SHGAT was built to fill.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-panel reveal-on-scroll">
    <span class="insight-panel-label">From retrieval to prediction</span>
    <p class="insight-panel-text">
      Retrieval finds the most similar past workflow. Prediction produces
      the next tool directly, conditioned on the current sequence. These are
      different problems with different failure modes. NB-01 and NB-02 proved
      that retrieval alone is insufficient; the GRU was built to predict.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="cinema-grid reveal-on-scroll">
    <figure class="cinema cinema-compact">
      <img src="/images/engine/deep/scaling/graph-vs-flat-scaling.png"
           alt="Graph-structured vs flat embedding retrieval accuracy across scales" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption><strong>NB-02 · Graph vs flat.</strong> Flat embeddings plateau at scale. Graph structure maintains retrieval quality as the catalog grows.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure class="cinema cinema-compact">
      <img src="/images/engine/deep/scaling/mp-toy-contrastive.png"
           alt="Contrastive message passing: different structural roles produce distinct representations" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption><strong>NB-01 · Contrastive MP.</strong> Structurally different nodes separate in representation space even when semantically similar.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <section class="deep-section">
    <h2>The Gap That Motivated Everything</h2>
    <p>
      NB-02 showed that at 920 leaf nodes, a pair of nodes can have near-identical
      embeddings but very different usage contexts — and very different nodes can
      co-execute reliably in sequence. Pure cosine similarity cannot distinguish
      either case.
    </p>
    <p>
      The decision to build SHGAT came from this: if you cannot retrieve the right
      tool by what it looks like, you need a model that knows where it fits — in
      the graph, in the sequence, in the hierarchy. That is what the full
      SHGAT + GRU pipeline provides.
    </p>

    <div class="scaling-stat-row">
      <div class="scaling-stat">
        <span class="scaling-stat-value">50</span>
        <span class="scaling-stat-label">workflows · retrieval works fine</span>
      </div>
      <div class="scaling-stat">
        <span class="scaling-stat-value">920</span>
        <span class="scaling-stat-label">leaf nodes · retrieval breaks down</span>
      </div>
      <div class="scaling-stat scaling-stat-accent">
        <span class="scaling-stat-value">SHGAT</span>
        <span class="scaling-stat-label">the response</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</DeepDiveLayout>

<style>
  /* ── Scaling panels ─────────────────────── */

  .scaling-panels {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto 48px;
    padding: 0 32px;
  }

  .scaling-panel {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 12px;
    padding: 24px;
    border: 1px solid var(--e-border);
    border-radius: 10px;
    background: var(--e-surface);
  }

  .scaling-panel-header {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 6px;
  }

  .scaling-nb {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--e-accent);
    opacity: 0.85;
  }

  .scaling-topic {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--e-text);
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    line-height: 1.2;
  }

  .scaling-body {
    font-family: 'Inter', system-ui, sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    line-height: 1.78;
    color: var(--e-text-secondary);
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* ── Insight panel ──────────────────────── */

  .insight-panel {
    max-width: 680px;
    margin: 0 auto 48px;
    padding: 24px 28px;
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--e-accent-glow), var(--e-surface));
    border: 1px solid var(--e-cinema-border);
    border-radius: 10px;
    margin-inline: 32px;
  }

  @media (min-width: 744px) {
    .insight-panel {
      margin-inline: auto;
    }
  }

  .insight-panel-label {
    display: block;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    color: var(--e-accent);
    opacity: 0.8;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }

  .insight-panel-text {
    font-family: 'Instrument Serif', Georgia, serif;
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--e-text-secondary);
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* ── Stat row ───────────────────────────── */

  .scaling-stat-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: 32px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: 40px;
    padding-top: 32px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--e-border);
  }

  .scaling-stat {
    text-align: left;
  }

  .scaling-stat-value {
    display: block;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--e-text-dim);
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }

  .scaling-stat-accent .scaling-stat-value {
    color: var(--e-accent);
  }

  .scaling-stat-label {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--e-text-dim);
    line-height: 1.4;
  }

  @media (max-width: 520px) {
    .scaling-panels,
    .insight-panel {
      padding-inline: 20px;
      margin-inline: 20px;
    }

    .scaling-panels {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .insight-panel {
      margin-inline: 20px;
    }
  }
</style>
